<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-975-508  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 975 508.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Dec 18 1989 v6 n50 p15(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Mountain Computer unveils 1-gigabyte tape drives. (FileSafe 1200,m FileSafe 7500) (product announcement)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Mountain Computer Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Mountain Computer Filesafe 7500 (Tape drive) (productintroduction)Mountain Computer Filesafe 1200 (Tape drive) (productintroduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionTape Drives.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Mountain Computer Inc. last week staked its claim in the fast-growing,high-capacity tape-drive market with a pair of systems capable of storingmore than 1 gigabyte of data, company officials said.andM;Mountain's new offerings fall into two categories: One unit marks thecompany's move into the Digital Audio Tape (DAT) arena, while the other joinsMountain's successful quarter-inch cartridge (QIC) line, said Tom Toperczer,vice president of marketing for the Campbell, Calif., firm.andM;Mountain's helical-scan DAT drive, the FileSafe 1200, stores 1.3 gigabytes ofdata and can be daisy-chained to provide up to 8.4 gigabytes of storage,officials said.andM;The 4mm FileSafe 1200 is the first in a planned line of DAT storage systemsfrom Mountain that will use the Digital Data Storage (DDS) recording formatdeveloped by Hewlett-Packard Co. and Sony Corp., the officials said.andP;  TheFileSafe 1200 will be available in February for $5,995.andM;Mountain's new QIC system, the FileSafe 7500, will also be available inFebruary in a 525M-byte, single-drive version and a 1.05-gigabyte, dual-driveunit.andP;  Prices for the units will start at $3,995.andM;Mountain Computer Inc. can be reached at (408) 379-4300.andO;</TEXT></DOC>